i# Preface		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe mobile phone I'm using today is Motorola Edge+ 2023, an Android		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iphone. To better customize my phone's functionalities, I unlocked its		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibootloader, and obtained root privileges, in order to install LSPosed		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand various LSPosed based plugins.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe root mechanism I'm using is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hKernelSU	URL:https://kernelsu.org/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, which works by modifying the Linux kernel to grant and only grant		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iroot permissions to certain apps. Although KernelSU provides official		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iGKI kernel images that work on most phones, I also flashed LineageOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ionto my phone, which is not compatible with GKI images. Therefore, I		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ihave to compile my own kernel.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince modifying the kernel's binary image is difficult, we usually		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iobtain the kernel source code under the GPLv2 license from the phone		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imanufacturer, modify it according to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hKernelSU's official guide	URL:https://kernelsu.org/guide/how-to-integrate-for-non-gki.html	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, and compile it into a full kernel.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Note: There is a new root mechanism		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
h> APatch	URL:https://apatch.dev/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> that works by modifying kernel binary image directly, and achieves		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> similar effects to KernelSU. I never use APatch, but it's worth a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> try if you don't want to compile your own kernel.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince KernelSU is widely used, some developers created GitHub Actions		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWorkflows, such as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://github.com/xiaoleGun/KernelSU_Action	URL:https://github.com/xiaoleGun/KernelSU_Action	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i. They can automatically patch the kernel source code and compile the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ikernel. However, as I tried some of these workflows, I found a few		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iproblems:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- These workflows will install multiple compilers alongside each		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  other, including the GCC that comes with GitHub Actions,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Android-specific		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
h  ARM32 GCC	URL:https://android.googlesource.com/platform/prebuilts/gcc/linux-x86/arm/arm-linux-androideabi-4.9/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
h  ARM64 GCC	URL:https://android.googlesource.com/platform/prebuilts/gcc/linux-x86/aarch64/aarch64-linux-android-4.9	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  provided by Google, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
h  Clang	URL:https://android.googlesource.com/platform/prebuilts/clang/host/linux-x86/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  . If the compilation parameters are not set correctly, different		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  parts of the kernel may be compiled with different compilers,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  creating a kernel that is unstable or wouldn't boot at all.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- These workflows only run on GitHub Actions and are difficult to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  debug locally.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- These workflows usually run on schedule or are manually triggered by		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  users. If they run on schedule, they recompile kernels even if there		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  are no source code changes, wasting compute resources. If they are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  manually triggered, users may not get the latest kernel updates in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  time.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince I have been using NixOS recently, I naturally thought of using		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe Nix package manager to solve these problems:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Nix creates an isolated environment when building packages, with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  only the compilers I specified. This prevents issues caused by		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  mixing compilers.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Nix package manager can run either locally on Linux, or on GitHub		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Actions. Since it creates the same isolated environment anywhere, I		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  can test the flow locally first, and then upload it to GitHub, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  confidently have Actions automatically compile updated kernels.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Nix also records all source code versions (actually source code		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  SHA256s) and the compilation commands when building packages. If		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  neither the source code nor the compilation command changes, Nix can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  reuse the last compilation results without repeating the work.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, I created a set of Nix-based scripts (actually Nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDerivations), to compile the kernel for my phone.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
