i## Preparing a Compiler		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe first thing to prepare for compiling kernel is to get a compiler.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe usual compiler for Android kernels is Clang, but the kernel for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isome older devices might be too old for Clang, and GCC must be used in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithis case.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iClang compiler is easy to get. Nixpkgs already has Clang packaged in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iit, and you can run `nix run nixpkgs#clang -- --version` to see the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilatest Clang version:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # nix run nixpkgs#clang -- --version		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  clang version 19.1.6		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Target: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Thread model: posix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  InstalledDir: /nix/store/2d1r5kvz7plg24bwb316972knqmiyf2p-clang-19.1.6/bin		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iClang itself supports cross compilation, and can produce ARM32 and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iARM64 binaries directly on x86_64 devices, without additional		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itoolchains. Therefore, the Clang compiler in Nixpkgs can be used		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idirectly.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThings get more complicated with GCC for older kernels. Nixpkgs		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ialready removed older GCCs, and as of now (Feb 2025) the oldest GCC in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNixpkgs is 9.5.0. In addition, GCC by default only supports compiling		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprograms to the same platform. A special GCC and toolchains is needed		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifor cross compiling ARM32/ARM64 kernels.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere I decided to take a short cut: I directly packaged Google's GCC		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompiler into Nix packages, so that they can be provided to the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompilation environment. Although Google has deleted the older GCC		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompilers from their servers, there are backups available on GitHub		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
