i## Obtain Kernel and KernelSU Sources		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWith the compiler ready, the next step is to obtain source code for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iboth the kernel and KernelSU. Since I'm using LineageOS, I can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idirectly download kernel source code from LineageOS's GitHub		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irepository:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://github.com/LineageOS/android_kernel_motorola_sm8550	URL:https://github.com/LineageOS/android_kernel_motorola_sm8550	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> You can also look for kernel source code from the manufacturer's		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> website. Since the Linux kernel is licensed under GPLv2, all phone		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> manufacturers must open source their modified kernel source code.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn the Nix package manager, you can use `fetchFromGitHub` to download		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ikernel source code from GitHub:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  fetchFromGitHub {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    owner = "LineageOS";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    repo = "android_kernel_motorola_sm8550";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    rev = "1bdeb4f5c8d2b98ef5f2bedaa5d704032dffd676";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    fetchSubmodules = false;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    sha256 = "sha256-ZK/DH5N5LdkLe48cANESjw1x74aXoZLFoMAwEDvzEk4=";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut this gives you the kernel source code at the commit specified by `rev`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iargument, with no automatic updates. To fix this, we can use		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hNvfetcher	URL:https://github.com/berberman/nvfetcher	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito automatically get the latest commit. First create a `nvfetcher.toml`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifile:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  [linux-moto-rtwo-lineageos-22_1]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  src.git = "https://github.com/LineageOS/android_kernel_motorola_sm8550.git"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  src.branch = "lineage-22.1"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  fetch.github = "LineageOS/android_kernel_motorola_sm8550"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAnd then run Nvfetcher: `nix run github:berberman/nvfetcher`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNvfetcher will download the latest commit based on your configuration,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand write it to `_sources/generated.nix` . Now you can use the kernel		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isource code from this file:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  let		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    sources = callPackage ../_sources/generated.nix { };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    sources.linux-moto-rtwo-lineageos-22_1.src		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWe can use the same approach for KernelSU, but since KernelSU only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isupports GKI kernels starting from 1.0, we can only use the last		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iversion 0.9.5 still has support for other kernels:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # nvfetcher.toml		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
